items.name: Kisaragi Reona TI
items.description:
The character from the not so popular Full Dive RPG anime. Very open ended model. Keeps the character, but will follow the prompts much closer with little need for weight adjustments. Works great at almost any step and scale config, compatible with most LoRAs and other embeddings.

To get the in-game outfit consistently, just type "fairy" into the prompt. Might also want to try adding "wings, thigh highs, gauntlets" for a closest match.

All training images were taken from r34, squared in paint3d, rescaled to 512x512 in birme, and then upscaled x4 in SD using R-ESRGAN. Trained at a rate of .0005 for 5k steps, but best result was around 3500-4200.

items.name: Vernon Roche | The Witcher 3 : Wild Hunt
items.description:
Character Lora of Vernon Roche from The Witcher 3 : Wild Hunt/ The Witcher 2: Assassins of Kings

"Temeria, that’s what matters." -Vernon Roche

101% BROche energy -soul3142


This work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives 4.0 International License.

If you want to, you can support me on Patreon or Buy me Coffee.

My Witcher LoRA Index - soul3142's Guide to the Witcher Universe.

Main Trigger Word - rocheW3 , check examples for other ones.

Recommendations :-

  1. Highres Fix - must, if you are getting blurry and ugly images

    My upscale method: txt2img 512x768 -> send to img2img -> controlnet tile upscale, tile diffusion 2x scale with 4xUltrasharp upscaler and tiled vae

  2. Weight: 0.7 - 0.8

  3. Clip Skip: 2

  4. Steps: 25-30

  5. CFG: 7-8

  6. Denoising - Don't go too high, it can alter a lot of details

I use 0.7 weight, 25 steps, Euler a, Clip skip 2 in nearly all my examples with almost same, simple +ve/-ve prompts regardless of checkpoint for my own consistency purposes.

There are imperfections here & there, which i usually leave it in as is, (i never do any inpainting in examples), most of which like hands can be fixed with better prompting, negative embeddings while other like weapons are just bad majority of the time no matter the model as of today.

Some LoRA's are flexible with any clothing, some are not (usually character's with single costume) so keep these things in mind.

This is an unofficial fanmade LoRA, not intended for any commercial purpose and use. All characters and IP rights are owned by their respective creators and owners. I do not own rights to any of these characters.

items.name: Comfyroll Custom Nodes for ComfyUI
items.description:
Comfyroll Custom Nodes For SDXL and 1.5

Custom nodes for SDXL and SD1.5 including Multi-ControlNet, LoRA, Aspect Ratio, Process Switches, and many more nodes.

Version 24 (13/9/2023)

  • Changed the CR Model Stack name from "CR Model Stack" to "CR Model Merge Stack"

  • CR Apply Model Merge node has been rewritten.

    • New method has been added to the Model Merge Apply

Installation

If you have a previous version of the Comfyroll nodes, please delete the existing folder before installing these nodes.

Install from Download

  • Place the zip file in \ComfyUI\custom_nodes\ and unzip

  • Move the zip file to an archive folder

  • Restart ComfyUI

Install from Git

  • cd custom_nodes

  • git clone https://github.com/RockOfFire/ComfyUI_Comfyroll_CustomNodes.git

  • Restart ComfyUI

Install using ComfyUI Manager

  • https://github.com/ltdrdata/ComfyUI-Manager

  • Restart ComfyUI

List of Custom Nodes

Logic

  • CR Image Input Switch

  • CR Image Input Switch (4 way)

  • CR Latent Input Switch

  • CR Conditioning Input Switch

  • CR Clip Input Switch

  • CR Model Input Switch

  • CR ControlNet Input Switch

  • CR Text Input Switch

  • CR Text Input Switch (4 way)

  • CR Switch Model and CLIP

Process

  • CR Hires Fix Process Switch

  • CR Img2Img Process Switch

  • CR Batch Process Switch

IO

  • CR Load LoRA

  • CR LoRA Stack

  • CR Apply LoRA Stack

Maths

  • CR Integer Multiple

Number

  • CR Seed to Int

  • CR Seed

Image

  • CR 1.5 Aspect Ratio

  • CR Color Tint

  • CR Halftone Grid

Conditioning

  • CR Apply Control Net

  • CR Multi-ControlNet Stack

  • CR Apply Multi-ControlNet Stack

SDXL

  • CR SDXL Aspect Ratio

  • CR SDXL Prompt Mix Presets

  • CR SDXL Style Text

  • CR SDXL Base Prompt Encoder

Module

  • CR Module Pipe Loader

  • CR Module Input

  • CR Module Output

  • CR Image Pipe In

  • CR Image Pipe Edit

  • CR Image Pipe Out

  • CR Pipe Switch

Latent

  • CR Latent Batch Size

Model Merge

  • CR Apply Model Merge

  • CR Model Merge Stack

Text

  • CR Integer To String

  • CR Float To String

Legacy

  • CR Image Output

  • CR Aspect Ratio SDXL

  • CR Aspect Ratio

  • CR SDXL Prompt Mixer

  • CR Image Size

Multi-ControlNet compatability with Efficiency nodes

CR LoRA Stack and CR Multi-ControlNet Stack are both compatible with the Efficient Loader node, in Efficiency nodes by LucianoCirino.

CR Apply Multi-ControlNet Stack can accept inputs from the Control Net Stacker node in the Efficiency nodes (see diagram in Images above).

Multi-ControlNet methodology

The method used in CR Apply Multi-ControlNet is to chain the conditioning so that the output from the first Controlnet becomes the input to the second.

For an example of this method see this link:

https://comfyanonymous.github.io/ComfyUI_examples/controlnet/#mixing-controlnets

Test Nodes

The nodes within this folder are previews of new nodes that we are working on. Know that if you use one of the nodes, be cautious because the design of the nodes might change before final release. If you have any feedback about the test nodes, you can make a post here or raise or issue on the github.

Credits

comfyanonymous/ComfyUI - A powerful and modular stable diffusion GUI.

WASasquatch/was-node-suite-comfyui - A powerful custom node extensions of ComfyUI.

TinyTerra/ComfyUI_tinyterraNodes - A selection of nodes for Stable Diffusion ComfyUI

SeargeDP/SeargeSDXL - Custom nodes and workflows for SDXL in ComfyUI

LucianoCirino/efficiency-nodes-comfyui - A collection of ComfyUI custom nodes.

SLAPaper/ComfyUI-Image-Selector - Select one or some of images from a batch

Github

https://github.com/RockOfFire/ComfyUI_Comfyroll_CustomNodes

https://github.com/Suzie1/Comfyroll-Workflow-Templates

items.name: Vikala (Granblue Fantasy)
items.description:
This is a lycors\locon you have to use the additional networks extension or the lycoris extension for this to work.

I was able to collect a good dataset while I was on vacation and I think this character is really cute and really deserves to skip some spots

Keyword is Vikala works on strength 1.0.

So now there is one thing that i messed up well two things

First off not enough pictures from behind so her sleeves can be kind of weird sometimes but that is a problem that these outfits have in general in my opinion.

Second problem which is a lot more relevant is that I tried to be cheesy and use some of her skins as well in the dataset because they were different enough from the base outfit. I only tried using some pictures of her swimsuit skin and that leads that she now has a thigh strap sometimes but i think you can get rid of it if you use bare legs or thigh strap in negatives.

Sadly her skin cant be reproduced so it's a fail/fail. Which doesn't break the model just that you know that it can happen and how you can prevent it.

The Image quality i got when generating was pretty good so im very happy about the result even if it is kind of flawed.

As always if you like it leave a comment, like it and rate it that would be appreciated.

Have fun generating.

items.name: DP's Realistic Mix
items.description:
The model generates realistic and semi-real pictures and tends to lean towards NSFW with some more basic prompts so you might need to add a few extra tags to work around that. It can also do different styles of art when you prompt for it correctly. There's only a few TI's and Lora's that haven't worked for me but I also had issues with them on other models so that might be unrelated.

Below is a short list of settings and tricks I use for basic txt2img gen. If you have any questions feel free to ask and I'll answer as best as I can.

If you enjoy using this I'd really like to see what you make with it so please share :)

Recommended Settings:

Prompting- The model can produce good results with very few prompts.

Try to keep negs to a minimum unless you happen to find a set that works.

If you are having issues still, try turning the prompt tokens below (:1) sometimes (:0.99) is all it takes. Some tokens can get over represented and will make the image distorted or baked. This can work for any model and helps with longer prompt strings. This is also true for img2img, lowering the token value will help prevent a baked picture if you want to keep the same seed. (:0.6-:0.8) Are good values to start with if you choose to do this and every word in the prompt can be manipulated in this way and will change the outcome.

Sampling Steps- 7-150, Also using a really low step count can give some very cool results if you plan on using hires.fix. 10-30 is a good place to start.

Sample Method- Any sample method works.

Restore Faces- Don't use it... Unless you plan on doing img2img or inpaint and only as a last resort.

CFG Scale- 4-10 Works for the majority of things. I've had a few prompts work with 15+ but not many. I normally use 4.5-9.

Hires.fix- For this you can do up to a 4x upscale but you need to use a 768x768 or lower resolution and lower the denoising strength the larger you upscale 0.2 or less usually for 4x. Start small then go big. I usually use x1.25-x2.

x1.1-x1.3 Upscaling you can go all the way up to 0.99 denoise value. (You will get a completely different picture but it will probably be coherent). For x1.5-2+ you will need to lower it to 0.7 or less. Most larger pictures I generate with 0.2-0.5.

This can generate 1:1 at 904x904 without hires.fix but there's a high risk of getting artifacts and distorted pictures.

768x768 or smaller will give the most consistent results. Also you can get away with a lot more with different aspect ratios at a larger scale. I seem to have good luck with 4:3 and similar sizes.

With hires.fix you can zoom in on something adding detail. For example you have a 512x768 picture and you want to x2 upscale to 1024x1536 you can instead set the sliders to something like 1024x1200 then you will get a cropped version of your picture that will have more detail added to it. It's a great trick if some parts of the picture refuse to turn out or you want to focus on the center of the picture more.

Img2Img-Inpainting- These work just about the same as txt2img and seem to work just fine. I've never really used inpainting specific models so I don't have any experiences to compare it against.

Remember! if it doesn't turn out right the first time change a few settings and try again :) its all about finding the sweet spots.

Have Fun and Enjoy!

Note that stable diffusion occassionally struggles with coloring parts individually or will mirror everything even when only training with non-mirrored images. The glove in particular has a tendency to either be the wrong color or bleed into the rest if the image. This could be fixed with more training steps at the cost of flexibility.

I have also included samples on how the model meshes with my Style LoRA. The style LoRA for ThiccWithaQ/Nyantcha works really well at replicating the original art.

Please leave a review if you enjoyed this Lora or have problems with it. I'd also be interested in how the lora behaves with other base checkpoints so why don't you give it a try and throw some images down below!

items.name: CZ-Art_Jiri-Trnka
items.description:
Hey! Hey!

I bring you the first LoRA from the series of Czech artists. Jiří Trnka was one of the most renowned illustrators and filmmakers. His children's books and films are considered national treasures. This LoRA is based only on his illustrations - we'll leave the film work for another time ;-)

How to:

  1. Choose a photorealistic checkpoint of your preference.

  2. Set LoRA Strength to 1.0, cfg around 7.0 and steps to 20.

  3. Choose your favorite sampler.

  4. That's it.

LoRA works best with children's book illustration themes. If you let your imagination run wild, it can handle it, but you'll get results roughly based on Trnka's work. Keep the prompts really simple, a negative prompt is actually almost unnecessary. Don't use magic words like 8K, masterpiece, etc. It will only push LoRA in the wrong direction. (OK, feel free to use them, I'm just saying you won't get typical results, which isn't necessarily a bad thing.) Try it and see.

HiresFix will make for better faces, but with high Denoise it starts making shit up again and moving away from the template.

items.name: Fantastic Rome
items.description:
Welcome to Fantastic Rome! Keep your hands and arms inside the chariot at all times, and don't feed the gladiators.

This tends to work without a trigger word, but add fantrome if you want to be sure it sticks to the theme. Add roman city for buildings without pillars in them. Add roman pillars for buildings with pillars. Add roman ruins to show the buildings in ruins. Add bath house to show big pools of water in an ancient and less sanitary version of swimming pools. Add roman soldier to show... well... a roman soldier. I also added a tiny number of images for chariots, but those were all paintings and I'm not even convinced they're roman, so your luck with using the chariot trigger may be quite low. I also have several pictures that depict something similar to a colosseum so use that keyword if you want something sort-of Colosseum looking, though it often looks weird and dominates the whole image. Note the spelling, since I intentionally did not use the word "coliseum" when tagging... just "colosseum".

I used a large dataset of ancient-rome adjacent things (sometimes more greek than roman, and sometimes fairly modern in the case of bath house but it works). I did not include any images of gladiators. Sorry, but I felt like gladiators deserved a well made lora of its own. I'm sure someone has a lora of buff gladiator looking dudes uploaded to civitai somewhere! :)
